        <h2>KUPPAM</h2>
        <p>Kuppam is a major town, revenue division, and mandal headquarters located in the Chittoor district of Andhra Pradesh, India. It is a critical administrative hub near the borders of Tamil Nadu and Karnataka. </p>
        <h2>Overview of Kuppam Mandal Grama Panchayat</h2>
        <p >
           <b> Location:</b> Situated roughly 125 km from Chittoor, 115 km from Bangalore, and 243 km from Chennai.
        </p>  
        <p>
            <b>Administration:</b> Kuppam is a Selection Grade Town Panchayat and acts as the headquarters for the Kuppam Revenue Division, which includes four mandals.
        </p>
        <p>
            <b>Villages:</b> The mandal comprises numerous villages including Adavi Budugur, Avulanatham, Bandasettipalle, Bevanapalle, and Chinna Bangarunatham.
        </p>
        <p>
            <b>Population:</b> As of the 2011 Census, Kuppam (town) had a population of 21,963, with an almost equal ratio of males (11,091) and females (10,872).
        </p>
        <p>
            <b>Infrastructure:</b> Key institutions include the Kuppam Rural Electric Co-operative Society (RECS), Horticulture Department (COE), Post Office, and multiple Grama Sachivalayams (Village Secretariats).
        </p>
        <p>
            <b>Key Rural Initiatives:</b> The area is active in the Pradhan Mantri Adarsh Gram Yojana (PMAGY), which includes developing Adarsh Grams (model villages) with various Grama Sabhas.
        </p>
        <b>Economic Highlights</b>
        <p>Kuppam's economy is a mix of heavy industry and advanced agriculture</p>
        <p><b>Granite Industry:</b> Famous globally for its unique "Kuppam Green" granite, the area has been a quarrying hub since 1925.</p>
        <p><b>Horticulture Hub: </b>The Kuppam Horticulture Hub (Centre of Excellence) uses Indo-Israeli technology to cultivate flowers and vegetables, significantly boosting farmer income.</p>    
         <p><b>Natural Farming:</b> An ambitious initiative aims to transition 70% of farmers and 50% of cultivable land to organic practices by 2028-29.</p>
        <p><b>Major Employers:</b> Industrial giants like Hindalco Industries and Hydro Extrusion India operate in the region. </p>


